# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2008-sichuan-earthquake
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1-000-000-000-number] In standard form, it is written as **1 × 109**.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1-000-000-000-number] The metric prefix giga indicates 1,000,000,000 times the base unit.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1-000-000-000-number] One billion years may be called an *eon* in astronomy or geology.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1-000-000-000-number] Previously in British English (but not in American English), the word "billion" referred exclusively to a million millions (1,000,000,000,000).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1-000-000-000-number] However, this is not common anymore, and the word has been used to mean one thousand million (1,000,000,000) for several decades.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1-000-000-000-number] The term ***milliard*** could also be used to refer to 1,000,000,000; whereas "milliard" is rarely used in English, variations on this name often appear in other languages.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1-000-000-000-number] In the Indian numbering system, it is known as 100 crore or 1 arab.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1-000-000-000-number] It is a common metric used in macroeconomics when describing national economies.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] The **1038 Dingxiang earthquake** devastated present-day Shanxi Province, northern China on 9 January.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] At least 32,300 people died across the province when the Ms 7.25 earthquake struck Dingxiang and Xinxian counties.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] In Xinzhou, about 19,742 people died and 5,655 were injured.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] More than 50,000 livestock also perished.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] About 759 were killed in Guoxian County and in present-day Taiyuan, 1,890 people died.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] The Xizhoushan Fault Zone, a strike-slip fault system within the Shanxi Rift System, may have been responsible for the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] Field studies indicate at least three earthquakes occurred along the fault during the Holocene with the most recent event possibly being the 1038 earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] This fault delineates the Xizhoushan Mountains and Xinding basin within the rift system.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] Estimates of the right-lateral slip rate range from 5.86–5.22 mm (0.231–0.206 in) per year to as low as 2 mm (0.079 in) per year during the Holocene.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] At least 60 km (37 mi) of surface rupture along the fault was associated with the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] Triggering of earthquakes in the rift system may have been due to the combined effects of coulomb stress transfer and long-term tectonic stress.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] In the case of the 1038 event, it was promoted by stress transfer from a previous Ms 7.5 earthquake in 512 AD.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1038-dingxiang-earthquake] This may have in turn promoted the Ms 6.5 earthquake near Taiyuan in 1102.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1290-chihli-earthquake] The **1290 Zhili earthquake** occurred on 27 September with an epicenter near Ningcheng, Zhongshu Sheng (Zhili), Yuan China.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1290-chihli-earthquake] This region is today administered as part of Inner Mongolia, China.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1290-chihli-earthquake] The earthquake had an estimated surface-wave magnitude of 6.8 and a maximum felt intensity of IX (*Violent*) on the Mercalli intensity scale.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1290-chihli-earthquake] One estimate places the death toll at 7,270, while another has it at 100,000.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1290-chihli-earthquake] The earthquake destroyed 480 storehouses and countless houses in Ningcheng.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1290-chihli-earthquake] Changping, Hejian, Renqiu, Xiongxian, Baoding, Yixian and Baixiang County were also affected.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1290-chihli-earthquake] It severely damaged the Fengguo Temple in Yixian.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] The 1303 **Hongdong earthquake** occurred in Yuan dynasty of the Mongol Empire, on September 25.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] The shock was estimated to have a moment magnitude of 7.6 and it had a maximum Mercalli intensity of XI (*Extreme*).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] This was one of the most deadly earthquakes in China, in turn making it one of the top disasters in China by death toll.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] In 2018, the epicentre was revised to be at 36°48′N 111°42′E﻿ / ﻿36.8°N 111.7°E﻿ / 36.8; 111.7 in what is now Xiamenzhen, to the southwest of the seat of Lingshi County, Shanxi.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] The epicentre had previously been determined to be 60 km south, in what is now Hongdong County.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] The earthquake likely occurred on the Taigu fault zone in Shanxi that part bounds the Taiyuan Basin, part of the Shanxi Rift System, and several scarps and uplifts of local faults were seen as evidence of this.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] The Taigu fault zone has not experienced any measurable activity since the 1303 earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] The magnitude was calculated by modern seismologists to be 8.0 on the moment magnitude scale, though it is impossible to say for sure due to lack of accurate geological data.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] Historical records and inscriptions typically asserted one of the three numbers to be the death toll: 170,000, 200,000+ and 270,000.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] This was one of the deadliest earthquakes in China, in turn making it one of the top disasters in China by death toll.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] In the nearby towns of Zhaocheng and Hongdong, every major temple and school building collapsed and over half the towns' populations perished.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] Every building in Huo county, Shanxi was destroyed.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] In Taiyuan and Pingyang, nearly 100,000 houses collapsed and over 200,000 people died from collapsing buildings and loess caves in a similar manner to the situation that would be experienced 253 years later in the 1556 Shaanxi earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] Cracks in the ground turned into miniature rivers, and many canals in Shanxi Province were destroyed, along with city walls.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] Some reports stated that the earthquake even levelled mountains and hills, altering the topographic make-up of the region.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] Landslides and soil subsidence and liquefaction triggered by the shaking were a likely root cause of these large-scale environmental changes.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] Rebuilding was generally slow, owing to the destroyed infrastructure of Shanxi and was interrupted by several other earthquakes in the following years.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] The 1303 Hongdong earthquake, though currently the last to have occurred on its fault system, marked the start of a centuries-long episode of heightened earthquake activity throughout China, the first of several to occur up to the end of the twentieth century.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1303-hongdong-earthquake] It was also the first of many examples of earthquakes that demonstrated the tendency of earthquakes in China to strike near loess plateaus.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] On 20 March 1536, Xichang (then known as Jianchang) and Mianning, Sichuan, Ming dynasty, were struck by an earthquake with an estimated magnitude of 7.3 Ms.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] It had a maximum felt intensity of X (*Extreme*) on the Modified Mercalli intensity scale, and caused thousands of deaths.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] Xichang lies on the eastern edge of the Tibetan Plateau, which is an area of thickened crust, which has been formed by the ongoing collision between the Indian Plate and the Eurasian Plate.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] The plateau is spreading laterally eastwards, to southeastwards, partly accommodated by a series of major strike-slip faults.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] The Sichuan–Yunnan block is bounded to the northeast and east by the left lateral Xianshuihe fault system and to the southwest by the right lateral Red River Fault.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] Xichang is sited at the southern end of the Anninge segment of the Xianshuihe fault system, close to its junction with the Zemuhe segment.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] Estimates for the magnitude of this earthquake vary in the range 7.3–7.5.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] Although the 1850 Xichang earthquake is thought to have ruptured both the Anninge and Zemuhe segments, the 1536 event probably only ruptured the more northerly Anninge segment.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] This is supported by paleoseismological investigations.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] A trench dug across the northern end of the Anninge segment found evidence of a rupture consistent with the 1536 event but a trench across the northern end of the Zemuhe segment lacked any such evidence.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] The extent of damage and casualties was reported by Yuancheng Cao, the official responsible for judging affairs in Sichuan.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] In Xichang all buildings were destroyed, including government offices, prisons, storehouses and houses (both military and civilian).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] The city walls, gates, battlements and watchtowers collapsed.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] Many people were crushed to death, including several senior officials.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] Further north in Mianning, every house was destroyed and the city walls completely collapsed and thousands were killed.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1536-xichang-earthquake] Parts of the city walls also collapsed in Yuexi, Qionglai, Ya'an, Dayi and Meishan.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] One of the deadliest earthquakes in history occurred in the early morning of 23 January, 1556 in Huaxian, Shaanxi, during the Ming dynasty.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Most of the residents there lived in yaodongs—artificial caves in loess cliffs—which collapsed and buried alive those sleeping inside.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Modern estimates by China Earthquake Administration's publications put the direct deaths from the earthquake at roughly 100,000, while over 700,000 either migrated away or died from famine and plagues, which summed up to a total reduction of 830,000 people in imperial *hukou* registration.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Huaxian lies within the Weihe Basin, one of the rift basins that form the southern and eastern boundaries of the Ordos Block.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] To the east the basin is continuous with the Shanxi Rift System.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The Weihe basin formed during the Paleogene in response to northwest–southeast directed extension.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Following a tectonically quiet period during the late Paleogene the rift basins became active again in the Neogene in response to NNW–SSE directed extension, activity that continues to the present.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The basins in the Weihe-Shanxi Rift System are bounded by large normal faults, which have been responsible for large historical earthquakes.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The Weihe Basin has an overall half-graben geometry, with the main controlling faults, such as the Huashan Fault and North Qinling Fault, forming the southern boundary.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The earthquake's epicenter was in the Wei River Valley in Shaanxi Province, near Huaxian (now Huazhou District of Weinan), Weinan and Huayin.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Huaxian was completely destroyed, killing more than half the residents of the city, with an estimated death toll in the hundreds of thousands.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The situation in Weinan and Huayin was similar.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] In certain areas, 20-metre-deep (66 ft) crevices opened in the earth.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Destruction and death were widespread, affecting places as far as 500 kilometres (310 mi) from the epicenter.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The earthquake also triggered landslides, which contributed to the massive death toll.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The rupture occurred during the reign of the Jiajing Emperor of the Ming dynasty.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Therefore, in the Chinese historical record, this earthquake is often referred to as the *Jiajing Great Earthquake*.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The earthquake damaged many of the Forest of Stone steles badly.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Of the 114 Kaicheng Stone Classics, 40 were broken in the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The scholar Qin Keda lived through the earthquake and recorded details.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] One conclusion he drew was that "at the very beginning of an earthquake, people indoors should not go out immediately.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Even if the nest has collapsed, some eggs may remain intact." The shaking reduced the height of the Small Wild Goose Pagoda in Xi'an by three levels.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Modern estimates, based on geological data, give the earthquake a magnitude of approximately Mw8.0 on the moment magnitude scale and XI (catastrophic damage) on the Mercalli scale, though more recent discoveries have shown that it was more likely Mw7.9.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Following the earthquake, aftershocks continued several times a month for half a year.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Shaking was felt strongly across the Weihe Basin region.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The maximum China seismic intensity was XI to XII occurring in Huaxian and Weinan.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] This would support the theory of the earthquake rupturing along the Huashan and Weinan faults.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Intensity VIII was observed throughout the basin and the intensity X+ zone was 100 km (62 mi) long.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Studies about the earthquake published between 1998 and 2017 presumed scarps along the Huashan and Weinan faults, some higher than 8 m (26 ft), were produced by the 1556 earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The fault zone is located northeast of Xi'an.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] This normal fault generally trends east–west and dips to the north.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] A 1995 study said scarps along the Huashan Fault were 3–8 m (9.8–26.2 ft) high.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Near the town of Huashan, the fault terrace contained Yangshao culture artifacts which were 4,000 years old.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] In a separate 1998 study, the fault scarps were about 4–7 m (13–23 ft) high.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Scarps of the Weinan Fault are less detailed in published works with most focused around the Chishui River area.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Two studies in 1992 and 2010 estimated the fault scarps at 2–4 m (6 ft 7 in – 13 ft 1 in) and 7–8 m (23–26 ft) respectively.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] There has not been any research to confirm these scarps were produced by the earthquake or formed by multiple events.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Assuming both faults ruptured during the earthquake, which runs for a total 90 km (56 mi), the Mw would be 7.0–7.5, according to empirical scaling relationships between magnitude and fault rupture length.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] This suggests previous values for the earthquake's magnitude were overestimated.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] More than 97 counties in the provinces of Shaanxi, Shanxi, Henan, Gansu, Hebei, Shandong, Hubei, Hunan, Jiangsu and Anhui were affected.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Buildings were damaged slightly in the cities of Beijing, Chengdu and Shanghai.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] In some counties as much as 60% of the population was killed.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Modern estimates by China Earthquake Administration's publications put the direct deaths from the earthquake to be roughly 100,000, while 730,000 either migrated away or died from famine and plagues, which summed up to a total reduction of 830,000 people in Imperial *hukou* registration.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] As the CEA did not estimate the total deaths (including subsequent famine and plagues), a handful of CEA staff scientists gave their own estimates, such as 450,000 or 530,000.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Millions of people at the time lived in yaodongs—artificial loess caves—on high cliffs in the Loess Plateau.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] Much of the population in some of the affected areas lived in yaodongs.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] This was a major contributing factor to the very high death toll.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The earthquake collapsed many caves and caused landslides which destroyed many more.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] The Portuguese Dominican friar Gaspar da Cruz, who visited Guangzhou later in 1556, heard about the earthquake, and later reported about it in the last chapter of his book *A Treatise of China* (1569).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1556-shaanxi-earthquake] He viewed the earthquake as a possible punishment for people's sins, and the Great Comet of 1556 as, possibly, the sign of this calamity (as well as perhaps the sign of the birth of the Antichrist).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The **1604 Quanzhou earthquake** was an extremely large seismic event that occurred in the Taiwan Strait, off the coast of Fujian Province, near Quanzhou during the Ming dynasty.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] According to modern-day calculations, the earthquake had a moment magnitude of 8.1 Mw.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] It is unknown how many casualties resulted from the quake, but major damage was reported.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The coast of Fujian Province, along the Taiwan Strait, is a tectonically stable part of the Eurasian Plate, therefore experience relatively low seismic activity.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The area forms part of the passive margin between the continental crust of the South China Craton and the oceanic crust of the South China Sea.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] Within the stable South China Craton, there are three zones of higher earthquake activity, one of which is the Southeast China Coast seismic zone running through Guangdong and Fujian.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] This zone follows the South China Maritime Fold Belt, which formed during a subduction event during the Late Jurassic to Early Cretaceous epochs.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The area is currently in a compressive stress regime with the maximum horizontal stress orientated northwest-southeast.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] This results from a combination of the continuing collision between the Indian and Eurasian Plates and the subduction of the Philippine Sea Plate.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The earthquake was associated with the Bingai Fault System of the Southeast China Coast seismic zone.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The Binhai Fault System, also known as the Littoral Fault System runs offshore in a north-northeast orientation for a total length of 500 km.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] Movement along the fault occurs in a right-lateral strike-slip fashion, although there is a small thrust component in it.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The fault was the source of large earthquakes in 1185, 1574, 1600, 1906, and most recently the 1918 Shantou earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] By modelling the earthquake and comparing the simulated seismic intensities against historical descriptions of the event, the moment magnitude of the quake is estimated at 8.1 Mw.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The model estimates a maximum coseismic slip of 16–20 meters along with the Bingai Fault System.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The rupture zone along the fault is estimated to be 250 km by 20 km.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] Two foreshocks occurred on December 22 and 28 in Anhai and Hui'an County, respectively.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The main shock on 29 December in the evening caused serious damage in the Minnan region.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] At least 22 counties across Fujian, Jiangxi, and Zhejiang suffered extensive destruction.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The quake was felt 1,000 km away in Anhui, Jiangsu, Shanghai, Hubei, Hunan, Guangdong, and Guangxi.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The maximum intensity near the coast has been evaluated to be IX (*Destructive*) on the China seismic intensity scale.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] Intensity VII (*Very strong*) was felt over an area of 20,669 km2.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] In Quanzhou, land slumping occurred, carrying many homes and shops away.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] Many roads, defensive wall, bridges and temples were destroyed.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] Liquefaction caused water and sand to erupt from the ground.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] Two rafters at the east pagoda of the Kaiyuan Temple, and eight at the southeast were destroyed.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] Severe damage also occurred on the Luoyang Bridge.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] Sulfur gases, sand and water was emitted from Mount Qingyuan.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] At Putian, sections of the defensive walls toppled.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] Tall buildings nearly collapsed while shorter homes were heavily damaged.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] In Yangwei, Xiakedi and Ligang, extensive fissuring occurred, with water and sand erupting.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] The battlements on the city walls of Nan'an fell.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/1604-quanzhou-earthquake] Severe damage was also reported in Haicheng, Fuzhou, Pinghe, Changtai, Shangyu, and Wenzhou.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] An earthquake occurred in the province of Sichuan, China at 14:28:01 China Standard Time on May 12, 2008.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Measuring at 8.0 Ms (7.9–8.3 Mw), the earthquake's epicenter was located 80 kilometres (50 mi) west-northwest of Chengdu, the provincial capital, with a focal depth of 19 km (12 mi).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The earthquake ruptured the fault for over 240 km (150 mi), with surface displacements of several meters.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The earthquake was also felt as far away as Beijing and Shanghai—1,500 and 1,700 km (930 and 1,060 mi) away, respectively—where office buildings swayed with the tremor, as well as Bangkok, Thailand and Hanoi, Vietnam.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Strong aftershocks, some exceeding 6 Ms, continued to hit the area up to several months after the main shock, causing further casualties and damage.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The earthquake also caused the largest number of geohazards ever recorded, including about 200,000 landslides and more than 800 quake lakes distributed over an area of 110,000 km2 (42,000 sq mi).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Over 69,000 people lost their lives in the quake, including 68,636 in Sichuan province.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] 374,176 were reported injured, with 18,222 listed as missing as of July 2008.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The geohazards triggered by the earthquake are thought to be responsible for at least one third of the death toll.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The earthquake left at least 4.8 million people homeless, though the number could be as high as 11 million.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Approximately 15 million people lived in the affected area.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] It was the deadliest earthquake to hit China since the 1976 Tangshan earthquake, which killed at least 242,000 people, and the strongest in the country since the 1950 Assam–Tibet earthquake, which registered at 8.6 Mw.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] It was the 4th deadliest natural disaster of the decade.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] It is the 18th deadliest earthquake of all time.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The economic loss of the earthquake was 845.1 billion yuan (US$130 billion).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] On November 6, 2008, the central government announced that it would spend 1 trillion yuan (about US$146.5 billion) over the next three years to rebuild areas ravaged by the earthquake, as part of the Chinese economic stimulus program.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] According to a study by the China Earthquake Administration (CEA), the earthquake occurred along the Longmenshan Fault, a thrust structure along the border of the Indo-Australian plate and Eurasian plate.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Seismic activities concentrated on its mid-fracture (known as Yingxiu-Beichuan fracture).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The rupture lasted close to 120 seconds, with the majority of energy released in the first 80 seconds.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Starting from Wenchuan, the rupture propagated at an average speed of 3.1 km/s (6,900 mph), 49° toward north east, rupturing a total of about 300 km (190 mi).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Maximum displacement amounted to nine metres (30 ft).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The focus was deeper than 10 km (6.2 mi).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In a United States Geological Survey (USGS) study, preliminary rupture models of the earthquake indicated displacement of up to nine metres (30 ft) along a fault approximately 240 km (150 mi) long by 20 km (12 mi) deep.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The earthquake generated deformations of the surface greater than three metres (9.8 ft) and increased the stress (and probability of occurrence of future events) at the northeastern and southwestern ends of the fault.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] On May 20, USGS seismologist Tom Parsons warned that there is "high risk" of a major M>7 aftershock over the next couple weeks or months.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] He pointed out that the shallowness of the hypocenter and the density of population greatly increased the severity of the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Teruyuki Kato, a seismologist at the University of Tokyo, said that the seismic waves of the quake traveled a long distance without losing their power because of the firmness of the terrain in central China.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] According to reports from Chengdu, the capital of Sichuan province, the earthquake tremors lasted for "about two or three minutes".
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The extent of the earthquake and after shock-affected areas lying north-east, along the Longmen Shan fault.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The Longmen Shan Fault System is situated in the eastern border of the Tibetan Plateau and contains several faults.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] This earthquake ruptured at least two imbricate structures in Longmen Shan Fault System, i.e. the Beichuan Fault and the Guanxian–Anxian Fault.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In the epicentral area, the average slip in Beichuan Fault was about 3.5 metres (11 ft) vertical, 3.5 metres (11 ft) horizontal-parallel to the fault, and 4.8 metres (16 ft) horizontal-perpendicular to the fault.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In the area about 30 kilometres (19 mi) northeast of the epicenter, the surface slip on Beichuan Fault was almost purely dextral strike-slip up to about three metres (9.8 ft), while the average slip in Guanxian–Anxian Fault was about two metres (6.6 ft) vertical and 2.3 metres (7.5 ft) horizontal.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The map of earthquake intensity published by CEA after surveying 500,000 km2 (190,000 sq mi) of the affected area shows a maximum *liedu* of XI on the China seismic intensity scale (CSIS), described as "very destructive" on the European Macroseismic Scale (EMS) from which CSIS drew reference.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The Yingxiu liedu-XI zone is about 66 km (41 mi) long and 20 km (12 mi) wide along Wenchuan–Dujiangyan–Pengzhou; the Beichuan liedu-XI zone is about 82 km (51 mi) long and 15 km (9.3 mi) wide along An County–Beichuan–Pingwu.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The area with liedu X (comparable to X on EMS, "destructive" and X on MM, "disastrous") spans 3,144 km2 (1,214 sq mi).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The area affected by earthquakes exceeding liedu VI totals 440,442 km2 (170,056 sq mi), occupying an oval 936 km (582 mi) long and 596 km (370 mi) wide, spanning three provinces and one autonomous region.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] QLARM (Quake Loss Alarms for Response and Mitigation) issues near-real-time estimates of fatalities and number of injured for earthquakes worldwide.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Recent alerts can be found on the web page of the International Institute for Earth Simulation Foundation.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Such an alert was issued 21 minutes after the May 12 Wenchuan earthquake of 2008.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] It had at first been assigned M7.5, internationally.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] This initial underestimate of the magnitude is a known problem with earthquakes of M8 and larger.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Based on the M7.5 information, QLARM distributed an email to about 300 recipients estimating that 1,000 to 4,000 fatalities had occurred.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] After learning that the earthquake may measure M8, QLARM distributed a revised estimate of 40,000 to 100,000 fatalities.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] This information was distributed within 100 minutes of the Wenchuan earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The news and official reports of fatalities are often strongly misleading.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] After the Wenchuan earthquake, officials led the public to believe for more than a week that the fatalities numbered only a fraction of what they really were (Figure 1).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] At the very beginning, everyone expects the news reports to be an initial count that will grow, not however, after one week.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] After such a long time, the false news reports take on a reality in their own right and the theoretical loss calculations by experts are discarded.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Once the extent of the rupture of the Wenchuan earthquake became known, QLARM calculated a more detail picture of the losses.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Figure 2 shows a map of the expected mean damage of the settlements affected by the Wenchuan earthquake on a scale of 5.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The resistance to shaking of buildings in large cities is assumed to be stronger than in villages, therefore the damage and percentage of fatalities in large cities is less than in villages.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Between 64 and 104 major aftershocks, ranging in magnitude from 4.0 to 6.1, were recorded within 72 hours of the main quake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] (The Ms6.1 earthquake on August 30, 2008, in southern Sichuan was not part of this series because it was caused by a different fault.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The earthquake had a magnitude of 8.0 Ms. and 7.9–8.3 Mw.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Office buildings in Shanghai's financial district, including the Jin Mao Tower and the Hong Kong New World Tower, were evacuated.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] A receptionist at the Tibet Hotel in Chengdu said things were "calm" after the hotel evacuated its guests.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Meanwhile, workers at a Ford plant in Sichuan were evacuated for about 10 minutes.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Chengdu Shuangliu International Airport was shut down, and the control tower and regional radar control evacuated.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] One SilkAir flight was diverted and landed in Kunming as a result.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Cathay Pacific delayed both legs of its quadruple daily Hong Kong to London route due to this disruption in air traffic services.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Chengdu Shuangliu Airport reopened later on the evening of May 12, offering limited service as the airport began to be used as a staging area for relief operations.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Reporters in Chengdu said they saw cracks on walls of some residential buildings in the downtown areas, but no buildings collapsed.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Many Beijing office towers were evacuated, including the building housing the media offices for the organizers of the 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] None of the Olympic venues were damaged.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Meanwhile, a cargo train carrying 13 petrol tanks derailed in Hui County, Gansu, and caught on fire after the rail was distorted.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] All of the highways into Wenchuan, and others throughout the province, were damaged, resulting in delayed arrival of the rescue troops.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In Beichuan County, 80% of the buildings collapsed according to Xinhua News.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In the city of Shifang, the collapse of two chemical plants led to leakage of some 80 tons of liquid ammonia, with hundreds of people reported buried.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In the city of Dujiangyan, south-east of the epicenter, a whole school collapsed with 900 students buried and fewer than 60 survived.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The Juyuan Middle School, where many teenagers were buried, was excavated by civilians and cranes.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Dujiangyan is home of the Dujiangyan Irrigation System, an ancient water diversion project which is still in use and is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The project's famous Fish Mouth was cracked but not severely damaged otherwise.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Both the Shanghai Stock Exchange and the Shenzhen Stock Exchange suspended trading of companies based in southwestern China.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Copper rose over speculations that production in southwestern China may be affected, and oil prices dropped over speculations that demand from China would fall.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Immediately after the earthquake event, mobile and terrestrial telecommunications were cut to the affected and surrounding area, with all internet capabilities cut to the Sichuan area too.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Elements of telecommunications were restored by the government piece by piece over the next number of months as the situation in the Sichuan province gradually improved.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Eventually, a handful of major news and media websites were made accessible online in the region, albeit with dramatically pared back webpages.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] China Mobile had more than 2,300 base stations suspended due to power disruption or severe telecommunication traffic congestion.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Half of the wireless communications were lost in the Sichuan province.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] China Unicom's service in Wenchuan and four nearby counties was cut off, with more than 700 towers suspended.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Initially, officials were unable to contact the Wolong National Nature Reserve, home to around 280 giant pandas.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] However, the Foreign Ministry later said that a group of 31 British tourists visiting the Wolong Panda Reserve in the quake-hit area returned safe and uninjured to Chengdu.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Nonetheless, the well-being of an even greater number of pandas in the neighbouring panda reserves remained unknown.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Five security guards at the reserve were killed by the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Six pandas escaped after their enclosures were damaged.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] By May 20, two pandas at the reserve were found to be injured, while the search continued for another two adult pandas that went missing after the quake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] By May 28, 2008, one panda was still missing.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The missing panda was later found dead under the rubble of an enclosure.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Nine-year-old Mao Mao, a mother of five at the breeding center, was discovered on June 9, her body crushed by a wall in her enclosure.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Panda keepers and other workers placed her remains in a small wooden crate and buried her outside the breeding centre.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The Zipingpu Hydropower Plant located 20 kilometres (12 mi) east of the epicenter was damaged.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] A May 24th inspection indicated that the damage was less severe than initially feared, and it remains structurally stable and safe.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] However, the Tulong reservoir upstream is in danger of collapse.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] About 2,000 troops have been allocated to Zipingpu, trying to release the pressure through a spillway.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In total, 391 dams, most of them small, were reported damaged by the quake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] According to Chinese state officials, the quake caused 69,180 known deaths including 68,636 in Sichuan province; 18,498 people are listed as missing, and 374,176 injured.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] This estimate includes 158 earthquake relief workers who were killed in landslides as they tried to repair roads.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] One rescue team reported only 2,300 survivors from the town of Yingxiu in Wenchuan County, out of a total population of about 9,000.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] 3,000 to 5,000 people were killed in Beichuan County, Sichuan alone; in the same location, 10,000 people were injured and 80% of the buildings were destroyed.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The old county seat of Beichuan was abandoned and preserved as part of the Beichuan Earthquake Museum.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Eight schools were toppled in Dujiangyan.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] A 56-year-old was killed in Dujiangyan during a rescue attempt on the Lingyanshan Ropeway, where due to the earthquake 11 tourists from Taiwan had been trapped inside cable cars since May 13.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] A 4-year-old boy named Zhu Shaowei (Chinese: 朱绍维) was also killed in Mianzhu when a house collapsed on him and another was reported missing.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Experts point out that the earthquake hit an area that had been largely neglected and untouched by China's economic rise.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Health care was poor in inland areas such as Sichuan, highlighting the widening gap between prosperous urban dwellers and struggling rural people.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In terms of school casualties, thousands of school children died due to shoddy construction.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In Mianyang City, seven schools collapsed, burying at least 1,700 people.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] At least 7,000 school buildings throughout the province collapsed.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Another 700 students were buried in a school in Hanwang.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] At least 600 students and staff died at Juyuan Elementary School.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Up to 1,300 children and teachers died at Beichuan Middle School.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] According to Tan Zuoren, 5,600 pupils were dead or missing from the 64 schools Tan investigated in the quake zone.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Tan was detained after he published such a casualties number.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Tang Xuemei was in a school dormitory building during the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] She was trapped for 28 hours before being rescued.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] She became a Paralympic sitting volleyball player and became Paralympic champion in 2012 winning the silver medal at the 2020 Summer Paralympics.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Niu Yu was in a school classroom building during the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] She was trapped for three days before being rescued.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] She became a disability rights advocate and walked with her prosthetic leg at the runway at Shanghai Fashion Week in 2021.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Details of school casualties had been under non-governmental investigation since December 2008 by volunteers including artist and architect Ai Weiwei, who had been constantly posting updates on his blog since March 2009.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The official tally of students killed in the earthquake was not released until May 7, 2009, almost a year after the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] According to the state-run Xinhua news agency, the earthquake killed 5,335 students and left another 546 children disabled.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Some parents believe the real figure is twice that officially cited.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The executive vice governor of Sichuan Wei Hong said the student death toll is 19,065.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Wei noted the toll was incomplete as the officials were still tallying the final number.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In the aftermath of the earthquake, the Chinese government declared that parents who had lost their only children would get free treatment from fertility clinics to reverse vasectomies and tubal ligations conducted by family planning authorities.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The earthquake left at least 5 million people without housing, although the number could be as high as 11 million.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Millions of livestock and a significant amount of agriculture were also destroyed, including 12.5 million animals, mainly birds.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In the Sichuan province a million pigs died out of 60 million total.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Catastrophe modeling firm AIR Worldwide reported official estimates of insurers' losses at US$1 billion from the earthquake; estimated total damage exceeded US$20 billion.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] It values Chengdu, at the time having an urban population of 4.5 million people, at around US$115 billion, with only a small portion covered by insurance.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Reginald DesRoches, a professor of civil and environmental engineering at Georgia Tech, pointed out that the massive damage of properties and houses in the earthquake area was because China did not create an adequate seismic design code until after the devastating 1976 Tangshan earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In the days following the disaster, an international reconnaissance team of engineers was dispatched to the region to make a detailed preliminary survey of damaged buildings.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Their findings show a variety of reasons why many constructions failed to withstand the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] News reports indicate that the poorer, rural villages were hardest hit.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Swaminathan Krishnan, assistant professor of civil engineering and geophysics at the California Institute of Technology said: "the earthquake occurred in the rural part of China.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Presumably, many of the buildings were just *built;* they were not designed, so to speak." Swaminathan Krishnan further added: "There are very strong building codes in China, which take care of earthquake issues and seismic design issues.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Strong aftershocks continued even months after the main quake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] On May 25, an aftershock of 6.0 Mw (6.4 Ms according to CEA) hit northeast of the original earthquake's epicenter, in Qingchuan County, Sichuan, causing eight deaths, 1,000 injuries, and destroying thousands of buildings.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] On May 27, two aftershocks, one 5.2 Mw in Qingchuan County and one 5.7 Mw in Ningqiang County, Shaanxi, led to the collapse of more than 420,000 homes and injured 63 people.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The same area suffered two more aftershocks of 5.6 and 6.0 Ms (5.8 and 5.5 Mw, respectively, according to USGS) on July 23, resulting in 1 death, 6 serious injuries, the collapse of hundreds of homes and damaging kilometers of highways.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] As late as August 5, yet another aftershock of 6.1 Ms (6.2 Mw according to USGS) hit Qingchuan, Sichuan, causing 1 death, 32 injuries, telecommunication interruptions, and widespread hill slides blocking roads in the area including a national highway.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Executive vice governor Wei Hong confirmed on November 21, 2008, that more than 90,000 people in total were dead or missing in the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] He stated that 200,000 homes had been rebuilt, and 685,000 were under reconstruction, but 1.94 million households were still without permanent shelter.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] 1,300 schools had been reconstructed, with initial relocation of 25 townships, including Beichuan and Wenchuan, two of the most devastated areas.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The government spent $441 billion on relief and reconstruction efforts.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party Hu Jintao announced that the disaster response would be rapid.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Just 90 minutes after the earthquake, Premier Wen Jiabao, who has an academic background in geomechanics, flew to the earthquake area to oversee the rescue work.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Soon afterward, the Ministry of Health stated that it had sent ten emergency medical teams to Wenchuan County.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] On the same day, the Chengdu Military Region Command dispatched 50,000 troops and armed police to help with disaster relief work in Wenchuan County.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] However, due to the rough terrain and close proximity of the quake's epicenter, the soldiers found it very difficult to get help to the rural regions of the province.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Premier Wen ordered the People's Liberation Army by saying, "It is the people who have raised you.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Even if it means walking on foot, you must nonetheless walk in there anyways.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] (Chinese: 是人民养育了你们, 你们自己看着办! 你们就是靠双腿走, 也要给我走进去)" However, PLA senior commander Guo Boxiong only listened to former CCP General Secretary Jiang Zemin's order, neither Wen Jiabao's or Hu Jintao's.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The first 72 critical rescue hours were wasted.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The National Disaster Relief Commission initiated a "Level II emergency contingency plan", which covers the most serious class of natural disasters.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The plan rose to Level I at 22:15 CST, May 12.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Many rescue teams, including that of the Taipei Fire Department from Taiwan, were reported ready to join the rescue effort in Sichuan as early as Wednesday.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The extreme terrain conditions precluded the use of helicopter evacuation, and over 300 of the Tibetan villagers were stranded in their demolished village for five days without food and water before the rescue group finally arrived to help the injured and stranded villagers down the mountain.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Persistent heavy rain and landslides in Wenchuan County and the nearby area badly affected rescue efforts.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] At the start of rescue operations on May 12, 20 helicopters were deployed for the delivery of food, water, and emergency aid, and also the evacuation of the injured and reconnaissance of quake-stricken areas.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] By 17:37 CST on May 13, a total of over 15,600 troops and militia reservists from the Chengdu Military Region had joined the rescue force in the heavily affected areas.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] A commander reported from Yingxiu Town, Wenchuan, that around 3,000 survivors were found, while the status of the other inhabitants (around 9,000) remained unclear.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The 1,300 rescuers reached the epicenter, and 300 pioneer troops reached the seat of Wenchuan at about 23:30 CST.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] By 12:17 CST, May 14, 2008, communication in the seat of Wenchuan was partly revived.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] On the afternoon of May 14, 15 Special Operations Troops, along with relief supplies and communications gear, parachuted into inaccessible Mao County, northeast of Wenchuan.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Beijing accepted the aid of the Tzu Chi Foundation from Taiwan late on May 13.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Tzu Chi was the first force from outside the People's Republic of China to join the rescue effort.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] China stated it would gratefully accept international help to cope with the quake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] A direct chartered cargo flight was made by China Airlines from Taiwan Taoyuan International Airport to Chengdu Shuangliu International Airport sending some 100 tons of relief supplies donated by the Tzu Chi Foundation and the Red Cross Society of Taiwan to the affected areas.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Approval from mainland Chinese authorities was sought, and the chartered flight departed Taipei at 17:00 CST, May 15 and arrived in Chengdu by 20:30 CST.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] A rescue team from the Red Cross in Taiwan was also scheduled to depart Taipei on a Mandarin Airlines direct chartered flight to Chengdu at 15:00 CST on May 16.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Francis Marcus of the International Federation of the Red Cross praised the Chinese rescue effort as "swift and very efficient" in Beijing on Tuesday.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] But he added the scale of the disaster was such that "we can't expect that the government can do everything and handle every aspect of the needs".
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The *Economist* noted that China reacted to the disaster "rapidly and with uncharacteristic openness", contrasting it with Burma's secretive response to Cyclone Nargis, which devastated that country 10 days before the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] On May 16, rescue groups from South Korea, Japan, Singapore, Russia and Taiwan arrived to join the rescue effort.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The United States shared some of its satellite images of the quake-stricken areas with Chinese authorities.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] During the weekend, the US sent into China two U.S.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Air Force C-17's carrying supplies, which included tents and generators.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Xinhua had reported a total of more than 100,000 Chinese troops, medics, and volunteers from other provinces that were involved in the rescue effort across 58 counties and cities in Sichuan.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The Internet was extensively used for passing information to aid rescue and recovery efforts.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] For example, the official news agency Xinhua set up an online rescue request center in order to find the blind spots of disaster recovery.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] After knowing that rescue helicopters had trouble landing into the epicenter area in Wenchuan, a student proposed a landing spot online and it was chosen as the first touchdown place for the helicopters.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Volunteers also set up several websites to help store contact information for victims and evacuees.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] On May 31, a rescue helicopter carrying earthquake survivors and crew members crashed in fog and turbulence in Wenchuan county, no one survived.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Rescue efforts performed by the Chinese government were praised by western media, especially in comparison with Myanmar's blockage of foreign aid during Cyclone Nargis, as well as China's previous performance during the 1976 Tangshan earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] China's openness during the media coverage of the Sichuan earthquake led a professor at the Peking University to say, "This is the first time [that] the Chinese media has lived up to international standards".
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] *Los Angeles Times* praised China's media coverage of the quake of being "democratic".
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Rescue efforts also came from Jet Li's One Foundation which saw the martial arts actor Wu Jing assisting in the efforts.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In Tuanshan Village, Longmenshan Town, Pengzhou, the Strong-Willed Pig was rescued suffering only skin trauma after being buried under rubble for 36 days.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The pig had survived off rainwater and charcoal, but lost 100 kg from its original 150 kg weight.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The Jianchuan Museum bought the pig from its original owner and gave the pig a new home on the museum premises.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] As of May 27, 2008, 34 lakes had formed due to earthquake debris blocking and damming rivers, and it was estimated that 28 of them were still of potential danger to the local people.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Entire villages had to be evacuated because of the resultant flooding.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] This operation was coupled with the work done by PLAAF Mi-17 helicopters bringing in PLA engineering corps, explosive specialists and other personnel to join 1,200 soldiers who arrived on site by foot.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Five tons of fuel to operate the machinery was airlifted to the site, where a sluice was constructed to allow the safe discharge of the bottle-necked water.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Downstream, more than 200,000 people were evacuated from Mianyang by June 1 in anticipation of the dam bursting.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The State Council declared a three-day period of national mourning for the quake victims starting from May 19, 2008; the PRC's National Flag and Regional Flags of Hong Kong and Macau Special Administrative Regions flown at half mast.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] It was the first time that a national mourning period had been declared for something other than the death of a state leader, and many have called it the biggest display of mourning since the death of Mao Zedong in 1976.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] At 14:28 CST on May 19, 2008, a week after the earthquake, the Chinese public held a moment of silence.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] People stood silent for three minutes while air defense, police and fire sirens, and the horns of vehicles, vessels and trains sounded.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Cars and trucks on Beijing's roads also came to a halt.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The Ningbo Organizing Committee of the Beijing Olympic torch relay announced that the relay, scheduled to take place in Ningbo during national mourning, would be suspended for the duration of the mourning period.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The route of the torch through the country was scaled down, and there was a minute of silence when the next leg started in city of Ruijin, Jiangxi on the Wednesday after the quake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Many websites converted their home page to black and white; Sina.com and Sohu, major internet portals, limited their homepages to news items and removed all advertisements.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Chinese video sharing websites Youku and Tudou displayed a black background and placed multiple videos showing earthquake footage and news reports.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The Chinese version of MSN, cn.msn.com, also displayed banner ads about the earthquake and the relief efforts.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Other entertainment websites, including various gaming sites, such as the Chinese servers for *World of Warcraft*, had shut down altogether, or had corresponding links to earthquake donations.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] After the moments of silence, in Tiananmen Square, crowds spontaneously burst out cheering various slogans, including "Long Live China".
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Even pay television channels (such as Channel V) had their programmes suspended.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] On the evening of May 18, CCTV-1 hosted a special four-hour program called *The Giving of Love* (simplified Chinese: 爱的奉献; traditional Chinese: 愛的奉獻), hosted by regulars from the CCTV New Year's Gala and round-the-clock coverage anchor Bai Yansong.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] It was attended by a wide range of entertainment, literary, business and political figures from mainland China, Hong Kong, Singapore and Taiwan.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Donations of the evening totalled 1.5 billion Chinese Yuan (~US$208 million).
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Of the donations, CCTV gave the biggest corporate contribution at ¥50 million.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Almost at the same time in Taiwan, a similarly themed programme was on air hosted by the sitting president Ma Ying-jeou.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In June, Hong Kong actor Jackie Chan, who donated $1.57 million to the victims, made a music video alongside other artists entitled "Promise"; the song was composed by Andy Lau.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The Artistes 512 Fund Raising Campaign, an 8-hour fundraising marathon, was held on June 1 in Hong Kong; it was attended by some 200 Sinosphere musicians and celebrities.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In Singapore, MediaCorp Channel 8 hosted a 'live' programme 让爱川流不息 to raise funds for the victims.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Although the Chinese government was initially praised for its response to the quake (especially in comparison to Myanmar's ruling military junta's blockade of aid during Cyclone Nargis), it then saw an erosion in confidence over the school construction scandal.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The central government estimates that over 7,000 inadequately engineered schoolrooms collapsed in the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Chinese citizens have since invented a catch phrase: "tofu-dregs schoolhouses" (Chinese: 豆腐渣校舍), to mock both the quality and the quantity of these inferior constructions that killed so many school children.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Due to the one-child policy, many families lost their only child when schools in the region collapsed during the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Consequently, Sichuan provincial and local officials have lifted the restriction for families whose only child was either killed or severely injured in the disaster.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] So-called "illegal children" under 18 years of age may be registered as legal replacements for their dead siblings; if the dead child was illegal, no further outstanding fines would apply.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Reimbursement would not, however, be offered for fines that were already levied.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] On May 29, 2008, government officials began inspecting the ruins of thousands of schools that collapsed, searching for clues about why they crumbled.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Thousands of parents around the province have accused local officials and builders of cutting corners in school construction, citing that after the quake other nearby buildings were little damaged.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] In the aftermath of the quake, many local governments promised to formally investigate the school collapses, but as of July 17, 2008, across Sichuan, parents of children lost in collapsed schools complained they had yet to receive any reports.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Local officials urged them not to protest but the parents demonstrated and demanded an investigation.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Furthermore, censors discouraged stories of poorly built schools from being published in the media and there was an incident where police drove the protestors away.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] On Children's Day, June 1, 2008, many parents went to the rubble of schools to mourn for their children.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The surviving children, who were mostly living in relief centres, performed ceremonies marking the special day, but also acknowledging the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Ye Zhiping, the principal of Sangzao Middle School in Sangzao, one of the largest in An County, has been credited with proactive action that spared the lives of all 2,323 pupils in attendance when the earthquake happened.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] During a three-year period that ended in 2007, he oversaw a major overhaul of his school.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] During that time he obtained more than 400,000 yuan (US$60,000) from the county education department, money used to widen and strengthen concrete pillars and the balcony railing of all four storeys of his school, as well as secure its concrete floors.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] The AP reported that "The state-controlled media has largely ignored the issue, apparently under the propaganda bureau's instructions.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] It was also reported that safety checks were to be carried out at schools across China after last month's earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] However, results from this inquiry have not been published.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Besides parents, Liu Shaokun (刘绍坤), a Sichuan school teacher, was detained on June 25, 2008, for "disseminating rumors and destroying social order" about the Sichuan earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Liu's family was later told that he was being investigated on suspicion of the crime of "inciting a disturbance".
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Liu had travelled to the Shifang, taken photos of collapsed school buildings, and put them online.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] He had also expressed his anger at "the shoddy tofu-dregs buildings" (豆腐渣工程) in a media interview.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] Liu was initially sentenced to one year of re-education through labor.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p01] However, Liu successfully appealed this decision and was allowed to return home and his belongings were returned.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Because of the magnitude of the quake, and the media attention on China, foreign nations and organizations immediately responded to the disaster by offering condolences and assistance.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] On May 14, UNICEF reported that China formally requested the support of the international community to respond to the needs of affected families.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] By May 14, the Ministry of Civil Affairs stated that 10.7 billion yuan (approximately US$1.5 billion) had been donated by the Chinese public.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Houston Rockets center Yao Ming, one of the country's most popular sports icons, gave $214,000 and $71,000 to the Red Cross Society of China.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The association has also collected a total of $26 million in donations.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Other multinational firms located in China have also announced large amounts of donations.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The Red Cross Society of China flew 557 tents and 2,500 quilts valued at 788,000 yuan (US$113,000) to Wenchuan County.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The Amity Foundation already began relief work in the region and has earmarked US$143,000 for disaster relief.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The Sichuan Ministry of Civil Affairs said that they have provided 30,000 tents for those left homeless.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Central State-owned enterprises have accumulatively donated more than $48.6 million.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] China National Petroleum Corp and Sinopec donated 10 million yuan each to the disaster area.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Following the earthquake, donations were made by people from all over mainland China, with booths set up in schools, at banks, and around gas stations.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] People also donated blood, resulting in according to Xinhua long line-ups in most major Chinese cities.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Many donated through text messaging on mobile phones to accounts set up by China Unicom and China Mobile By May 16, the Chinese government had allocated a total of $772 million for earthquake relief so far, up sharply from $159 million from May 14.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] On May 16 China stated it had also received $457 million in donated money and goods for rescue efforts so far, including $83 million from 19 countries and four international organizations.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Saudi Arabia was the largest aid donor to China, providing close to €40,000,000 in financial assistance, and an additional €8,000,000 worth of relief materials.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] A total of 45.5 million members of the Chinese Communist Party contributed financially to the special fund for relief, donating a total of around US$1.37 billion.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Saudi Arabia was one of the largest foreign donors in response to the 2008 Sichuan (Wenchuan) earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] King Abdullah bin Abdul-Aziz offered US$50 million in cash and US$10 million in relief materials.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The relief materials included tents, blankets, instant food, milk powder, and rescue tools.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Saudi Arabia also pledged further supplies, including approximately 85,000 tents, 400,000 awnings, and 500,000 blankets.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] To support displaced families, Saudi Arabia established a sheltering center in Mima Netso, Sichuan (covering about 30,000 m2), capable of sheltering over 15,000 families with more than 11,300 tents, and including health clinic facilities.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Employees of both governments coordinated on airlifting and distribution of aid.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Chinese government officials publicly thanked Saudi Arabia, noting the assistance reflected strong bilateral friendship.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] On May 12, 2009, China marked the first anniversary of the quake with a moment of silence as people across the nation remembered the dead.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The government also opened access to the sealed ruins of the Beichuan County seat for three days, after which it would be frozen in time as a state earthquake relic museum in remembrance of the disaster.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The Wenchuan Earthquake Memorial is located at the ancient town of Anren in Dayi County, the former site of Beichuan Middle School.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The earthquake was the worst to strike the Sichuan area in over 30 years.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Following the quake, experts and the general public sought information on whether or not the earthquake could have been predicted, and whether or not studying statistics related to the quake could result in better prediction of earthquakes in the future.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Earthquake prediction is not yet established science; there was no consensus within the scientific community that earthquake "prediction" is possible.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] In 2002, Chinese geologist Chen Xuezhong published a *Seismic Risk Analysis* study in which he came to the conclusion that beginning with 2003, attention should be paid to the possibility of an earthquake with a magnitude of over 7.0 occurring in Sichuan region.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] He based his study on statistical correlation.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] That Sichuan is a seismically active area has been discussed for years prior to the quake, though few studies point to a specific date and time.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Seismologist Gary Gibson of Monash University in Australia told Deutsche Presse-Agentur that he also did not see anything that could be regarded as having 'predicted' the earthquake's occurrence.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The earthquake also provided opportunities for researchers to retrofit data in order to model future earthquake predictions.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Using data from the Intermagnet Lanzhou geomagnetic observatory, geologists Lazo Pekevski from the Ss.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Cyril and Methodius University of Skopje in North Macedonia and Strachimir Mavrodiev from the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences attempted to establish a "time prediction method" through collecting statistics on geomagnetism with tidal gravitational potential.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Using this method, they were said to have predicted the time of the 2008 Sichuan earthquake with an accuracy of ±1 day.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The same study, however, acknowledges the limitation of earthquake prediction models, and does not mention that the *location* of the quake could be accurately predicted.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] An article in *Science* suggested that the construction and filling of the Zipingpu Dam may have triggered the earthquake.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The effect was "25 times more" than a year's worth of natural stress from tectonic movement.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The government had disregarded warnings about so many large-scale dam projects in a seismically active area.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Researchers have been denied access to seismological and geological data to examine the cause of the quake further.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] Geng's drought-earthquake correlation theory was first released in 1972, and said to have predicted the 1975 Haicheng and 1976 Tangshan earthquakes.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] The same *Yazhou Zhoukan* article pointed out the inherent difficulties associated with predicting earthquakes.
[src:2008-sichuan-earthquake/2008-sichuan-earthquake-p02] In response, an official with the Seismological Bureau stated that "earthquake prediction is widely acknowledged around the world to be difficult from a scientific standpoint." The official also denied that the Seismological Bureau had received reports predicting the earthquake.
